			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">August 25, 2014 9:12 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/08/25/absorbing-events-past-in-a-summers-reading-list/" data-title="Absorbing Events Past in a Summer&#8217;s Reading List" data-description="Andrew Ross Sorkin&#039;s summer reading list on the meanderings of business, finance and technology. ">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As the summer comes to an end, Iâve been trying to squeeze as much reading as I can into the final days. A benefit of this job is the opportunity to get sneak peeks at books before they are released, so Iâve been catching up on a pile of books that I missed earlier in the year as well as trying to get ahead by polishing off a couple that wonât be published until later this fall. So while <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=AMZN&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Amazon.com Inc">Amazon</a>âs <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/b/jeffrey_p_bezos/index.html?inline=nyt-per" class="tickerized" title="More articles about Jeffrey P. Bezos">Jeff Bezos</a> continues to battle it out with Hachette (now that should be a book!), hereâs a list of highlights from my summer reading list that I hope will appeal to your inner financial geek:</p>
<div class="w190 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/08/26/business/Sorkin2/Sorkin2-articleInline.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/08/26/business/Sorkin2/Sorkin2-articleInline.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/08/26/business/Sorkin2/Sorkin2-articleInline.jpg" id="100000003074388" width="190" height="280" alt="A look at the banking crisi: âThe Shifts and the Shocksâ by Martin Wolf."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="280"><meta itemprop="width" content="190"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">A look at the banking crisi: âThe Shifts and the Shocksâ by Martin Wolf.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> </span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe Shifts and the Shocks: What Weâve Learned â and Have Still to Learn â from the Financial Crisis,â by Martin Wolf, the economic columnist at The Financial Times. The book, to be published on Sept. 11, the anniversary of the week of the financial crisis in 2008, is a surprisingly refreshing look at the biggest financial calamity since <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/subjects/g/great_depression_1930s/index.html?inline=nyt-classifier" class="tickerized" title="Recent and archival news about the Great Depression.">the Great Depression</a>. Just when you thought everything that could be said about the crisis had been said, Mr. Wolf adds something new. This isnât a tick-tock â the journalistic term for a play-by-play â version of the crisis. Itâs more of an academic book. Nonetheless, Mr. Wolf deftly weaves together the components of the crisis, examining it from 10,000 feet up: globalization, monetary policy, banking architecture. Heâs best when heâs arguing about characters like <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/k/john_maynard_keynes/index.html?inline=nyt-per" class="tickerized" title="More articles about John Maynard Keynes.">John Maynard Keynes</a>. While Mr. Wolf is tough on the banks, heâs slightly less tough on the regulators: <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/b/ben_s_bernanke/index.html?inline=nyt-per" class="tickerized" title="More articles about Ben S. Bernanke">Ben Bernanke</a>, the former <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/f/federal_reserve_system/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More articles about the Federal Reserve System.">Federal Reserve</a> chairman, and Mervyn King, the former governor of the <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/b/bank_of_england/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More articles about Bank of England.">Bank of England</a>, both have glowing blurbs about the book on the jacket cover.</p>
<div class="w190 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/08/26/business/Sorkin1/Sorkin1-articleInline.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/08/26/business/Sorkin1/Sorkin1-articleInline.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/08/26/business/Sorkin1/Sorkin1-articleInline.jpg" id="100000003074372" width="190" height="280" alt="A look at the Internetâs parents: âThe Innovatorsâ by Walter Isaacson."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="280"><meta itemprop="width" content="190"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">A look at the Internetâs parents: âThe Innovatorsâ by Walter Isaacson.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> </span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">One of my favorite biographers is Walter Isaacson, who has made a career out of profiling geniuses and power: <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/e/albert_einstein/index.html?inline=nyt-per" class="tickerized" title="More articles about Albert Einstein.">Albert Einstein</a>, <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/f/benjamin_franklin/index.html?inline=nyt-per" class="tickerized" title="More articles about Benjamin Franklin">Benjamin Franklin</a>, <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/k/henry_a_kissinger/index.html?inline=nyt-per" class="tickerized" title="More articles about Henry A. Kissinger.">Henry Kissinger</a> and, most recently, <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/j/steven_p_jobs/index.html?inline=nyt-per" class="tickerized" title="More articles about Steven P. Jobs.">Steve Jobs</a>. His latest book, âThe Innovators: How a Group of Hackers, Geniuses, and Geeks Created the Digital Revolution,â will be published on Oct. 7. It isnât about one individual genius. Rather, it is a series of profiles of dozens of geniuses who collectively helped create the modern digital world. The book is filled with gems of no-names (at least to most of us) whose seemingly small ideas had huge impacts. For example, he introduces the reader to J.C.R. Licklider, &#8220;a laconic yet oddly charming psychologist and technologist&#8221; known as âLickâ at the <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/m/massachusetts_institute_of_technology/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More articles about the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.">Massachusetts Institute of Technology</a> who became a father figure of the Internet, and William Shockley, a physicist who was among those who invented the transistor.  The author quotes a journal in which Shockley wrote of his transistors: âIdea of setting world on fire, father proud.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Hereâs a book for the true finance nerd: âMoney and Tough Love: On Tour With the I.M.F.,â by Liaquat Ahamed. Mr. Ahamed is the Pulitzer Prize-winning author of âLords of Finance,â one of the great historical narratives about central bankers. My colleague Joe Nocera called that book âa magisterial work.â Mr. Ahamedâs latest effort is not nearly as ambitious â it is more like a financial travelogue than a full book (it includes pictures) â but it made me interested in the <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/i/international_monetary_fund/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More articles about the International Monetary Fund.">International Monetary Fund</a>, an institution that I never fully appreciated. Most people think the I.M.F. is some kind of financial <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/u/united_nations/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More articles about the United Nations.">U.N.</a>, but have no real understanding of how it works. âMoney and Tough Loveâ isnât as rich as âLords of Finance,â but it is an instructive text. The I.M.F. is, with the exception of central banks, the worldâs chief bailout provider. This book isnât personality-driven â thereâs not much new color on Christine Lagarde, the French managing director of the fund â but there is a lot of detail about the inner workings. âThis was to be about the troops, not the generals,â he writes early on. Still, it is full of fun anecdotes and telling descriptions. He quotes John Paul Getty saying: âIf you owe the bank $100, thatâs your problem. But if you owe the bank $100 million, thatâs the bankâs problem.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">If you want to understand China, to really get a visceral feel for the issues facing the country and its economy, the most readable book Iâve found is âAge of Ambition: Chasing Fortune, Truth, and Faith in the New China,â by Evan Osnos of <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/n/the_new_yorker/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More articles about The New Yorker.">The New Yorker</a>. Judith Shapiro, in a review in The New York Times, called it âa riveting and troubling portrait of a people in a state of extreme anxiety about their identity, values and future,â and thatâs exactly what it is. The book helped me fully appreciate the Chinese aspiration for great wealth and power as well as the challenges and corruption that pervade the political system.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">We donât like to admit it, but most of us are besieged by all of our commitments to work, family and friends. Brigid Schulte, a reporter for The Washington Post, has written âOverwhelmed: Work, Love and Play When No One Has the Time,â which not only captures the conundrum so many people face but also offers some practical solutions. Itâs not a self-help book per se, but I found many of the anecdotes and stories personally instructive. Note: âOverwhelmedâ is written in large part for women in the work force â Ms. Schulte writes a lot about her own experiences â but I found it to be just as relevant for me. My biggest takeaway: Try finding activities that force your mind to stop spinning about whatever youâre obsessing over. Itâs called âactive play.â So instead of going to the gym, for example, Ms. Schulte goes for a trapeze lesson â whatever you were obsessing over before, itâs hard to think of much else when youâre dangling high above a net. In the end, however, she learns, as I did, âthe overwhelm never goes away. But you can change how you think about it.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This last book has flown under the radar but deserves to be highlighted as simply a delightful memoir. âSo Much to Do: A Full Life of Business, Politics, and Confronting Fiscal Crisesâ is by Richard Ravitch, a former lieutenant governor of New York and co-chairman, with <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/v/paul_a_volcker/index.html?inline=nyt-per" class="tickerized" title="More articles about Paul A. Volcker.">Paul Volcker</a>, of the task force on the state budget. Mr. Ravitch shares an office to this day with Mr. Volcker in Rockefeller Center. It is a small book, but it is filled with great stories and lessons about state government, New York City and the influence of money in politics and life. In one rather funny vignette, Mr. Ravitch describes his effort to persuade <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/s/george_m_steinbrenner_iii/index.html?inline=nyt-per" class="tickerized" title="More articles about George M. Steinbrenner III.">George Steinbrenner</a>, the former owner of the New York Yankees, to allow the Mets to play in <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/y/yankee_stadium/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More articles about Yankee Stadium.">Yankee Stadium</a> for two summers so the city could rebuild Shea Stadium as part of a bid to make New York City the host of the Olympic Games in 1984. Mr. Steinbrenner âtold me in classic language just what physically impossible act I should perform on myself,â he wrote.</p>
